<% end %>

If you want an overview of what motivates people to do stuff then check out this book. The book is based on Chou's Octalysis framework - which despite the ridiculous name is actually really good.

This is super useful for external aspects like community and product design, as well as getting your team more engaged.

### [Traction - Gabriel Weinberg & Justin Mares](https://www.amazon.com/Traction-Startup-Achieve-Explosive-Customer/dp/1591848369)

<% link_to "https://www.amazon.com/Traction-Startup-Achieve-Explosive-Customer/dp/1591848369" do %>
    <%= image_tag "21-startup-books-that-changed-the-way-i-think/traction.jpg" %>
<% end %>

Traction picks up after that and focuses on acquisition. The book gives a complete overview of growth channels available to startups and a framework for thinking about them. Regardless of where in the business you are you need to have an understand of growth levers - as Paul Graham says, “Startup = growth”.

The book talks about a bullseye framework, which feels quite underdeveloped. For another take on growth frameworks I recommend checking out [Hacking Growth](https://www.amazon.com/Hacking-Growth-Fastest-Growing-Companies-Breakout/dp/045149721X) by Sean Ellis, who was the guy that designed the Dropbox referral program.

